The Federal Reserve‚Äôs digital payments system, which it promises will help speed up the way money moves around the world, will debut in July.

The system will allow bill payments, money transfers such as paychecks and disbursements from the government, as well as a host of other consumer activities to move more rapidly and at lower cost, according to the program‚Äôs goals.

Participants will complete a training and certification process in early April, according to a Fed announcement.

‚ÄúWith the launch drawing near, we urge financial institutions and their industry partners to move full steam ahead with preparations to join the FedNow Service,‚Äù said Ken Montgomery, the program executive and first vice president at the Boston Fed, which helped spearhead the project under former Boston Fed President Eric Rosengren.

Institutions that participate in the program will have seven-day, 24-hour access, as opposed to a system currently in place that closes on weekends.
